This patch introduces two new operands applicable to both qnum and qubit types. The first is bitlength, a unary prefix builtin that returns the number of qubits in a qnum or qubit register as a cnum. For a qubit this always returns 1. The second is amplitude indexing via register[x] and register['bstr'], which reads or writes the complex amplitude of a specific basis state within the quantum register's superposition. Index access by integer selects by basis state index in standard binary computational basis order (000=0, 001=1, 010=2, and so on). Index access by quoted binary string selects by the explicit bit pattern. On read, the expression yields a cnum by default; if assigned to a qnum variable the cnum is used to initialise a quantum register from that scalar value. On write, the right-hand side may be a cnum or a qnum; if it is a qnum it is measured to produce a scalar amplitude consistent with the Janus rule that assigning a quantum value into a classical context causes measurement. After any write the register is automatically renormalised.
New Syntax
bitlength(q)   -- returns number of qubits in q as cnum; q may be qnum or qubit
bitlength q    -- unary prefix form
q[3]           -- read amplitude at basis index 3, yields cnum by default
q['010']       -- read amplitude at basis state |010>, yields cnum by default
q[3] = v       -- set amplitude at basis index 3 to v (cnum or qnum), then renormalise
q['010'] = v   -- set amplitude at basis state |010> to v (cnum or qnum), then renormalise
Return Types
bitlength: always cnum.
register[x] read: cnum by default; coerces to qnum if assigned to a qnum variable, following standard Janus numeric-to-quantum coercion.
register[x] = v write: cnum representing the scalar amplitude that was written (after measuring v if v was a qnum, before renormalisation of the register).
Error Conditions
An integer index >= 2^(num_qubits) is a runtime error. A string index whose length does not equal the register's qubit count is a runtime error. A string index containing any character other than '0' or '1' is a runtime error. No zero-padding of short string indices is performed. The target of a quantum amplitude write assignment (register[x] = v) must be a plain identifier at the type-check stage; a non-identifier target is a compile-time error.
Design Notes
bitlength is added as a new keyword KW_BITLENGTH throughout the pipeline. The existing IndexExpr AST node is reused for quantum amplitude access. The type checker resolves the result of a quantum amplitude read IndexExpr to CNUM; coercion to QNUM when the read is assigned to a qnum variable is handled by the existing numeric-to-quantum assignment coercion path already present in the backend. The type checker accepts cnum or qnum on the right-hand side of a quantum amplitude write assignment; if the right-hand side is qnum the IR gen and backend apply measurement before using the result as the amplitude scalar, consistent with existing Janus quantum-to-classical coercion. The type checker enforces at compile time that the target of a quantum amplitude write is a plain IdentifierExpr. In the IR, two new nodes IRQnumIndex and IRQnumIndexAssign represent quantum amplitude read and write distinctly from the general collection index path so both backends can dispatch without re-examining the object type. String-index binary address validation is a runtime check only. Renormalisation after write uses the existing QuantumState::normalise method.
